'''Salt toxicosis''' is the overconsumption of [[salt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merckvetmanual.com/toxicology/salt-toxicity/overview-of-salt-toxicity|title=Salt Toxicity|author=  Larry J. Thompson, DVM, PhD, DABVT, Senior Research Scientist, Nestlé Purina PetCare|publisher=Merck & Co., Inc., Kenilworth, NJ, USA}}</ref> The symptoms may include (in the [[gastrointestinal tract]] and specifically a human's tract) a [[swollen tongue]], [[nausea]], [[vomiting]], [[diarrhea]], [[abdominal cramp]]s, and [[thirst]]. [[Neurological]] effects may include [[thirst]], [[irritability]], [[weakness]], [[headache]], and [[convulsion]]s. [[Cerebral edema]] may also occur, and [[muscle tremor]]s can also be present.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/a?dbs+hsdb%3A%40term+%40DOCNO+6368|title=Sodium Chloride and the Human Health affects|author=Dart, R.C. (ed). Medical Toxicology. Third Edition, Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. Philadelphia, PA. 2004., p. 1058}}</ref> Salt toxicosis also affects many breeds of pets or domesticated animals, such as [[cat]]s, [[dog]]s, [[horse]]s, [[cow]]s, and [[bird]]s. Symptoms for pets may include vomiting, diarrhea, [[inappetence]], [[lethargy]], walking drunk, abnormal fluid accumulation within the body, excessive thirst or [[urination]], potential injury to the [[kidney]]s, [[tremor]]s, [[seizure]]s, [[coma]], and eventually could lead to death without care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petpoisonhelpline.com/poison/salt/|title=Salt and Dogs, Salt and Cats - Salt Poisoning in Cats and Dogs |publisher=Pet Poison Hotline}}</ref>

Salt toxicosis may be caused by the [[ingestion]] of [[salt dough]].{{cn|date=March 2018}}

